{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522702","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522702"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:47:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:47:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13841"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13841","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13841"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.03,0.07,0.07,0.81]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6458"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50834"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6458","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6458"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13841"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36070"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"1866"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12768"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12769"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35140"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50834","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50834"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 18-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of fever, cough, runny nose, and red eyes. Today, a rash has appeared on his face and is spreading down his body. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisation status is unclear. On examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 39.2\u00b0C. A maculopapular rash is visible on his face, trunk, and upper extremities (Image 1 and Image 2). Examination of his mouth reveals white spots on the buccal mucosa.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Erythema infectiosum","Roseola","Rubella","Scarlet fever","Measles"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation described is highly suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003Emeasles\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient exhibits the classic triad of symptoms known as the \u00273 Cs\u0027: cough, coryza (runny nose), and conjunctivitis (red eyes), which typically precede the rash by 2-4 days. The maculopapular rash that begins on the face and spreads downward is characteristic of measles. Most importantly, the presence of white spots on the buccal mucosa, likely Koplik spots, is pathognomonic for measles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERubella\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as German measles, typically presents with a milder illness and a more subtle rash. The rash in rubella is often described as pink and less confluent than in measles. Rubella does not cause Koplik spots.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERoseola\u003C/strong\u003E, caused by human herpesvirus 6, typically affects infants and young children. It is characterized by high fever for several days, followed by a rash that appears as the fever breaks. The rash in roseola is usually more fine and pink, and it doesn\u0027t typically start on the face.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScarlet fever\u003C/strong\u003E, caused by group A \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus\u003C/em\u003E, presents with a sandpaper-like rash that typically starts in the groin and axillae before spreading. It is often accompanied by a strawberry tongue and pharyngitis, which are not described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErythema infectiosum\u003C/strong\u003E, or fifth disease, caused by parvovirus B19, typically presents with a \u0027slapped cheek\u0027 appearance followed by a lacy rash on the trunk and extremities. It is usually a mild illness and doesn\u0027t cause the severe symptoms described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of prodromal symptoms (fever, cough, coryza, conjunctivitis), the characteristic rash progression, and the presence of Koplik spots make measles the most likely diagnosis. This case highlights the importance of recognizing the classic presentation of measles, especially in unvaccinated or partially vaccinated individuals. Prompt diagnosis is crucial for implementing appropriate isolation measures and preventing further spread of this highly contagious disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Measles typically presents with a characteristic maculopapular rash that spreads cephalocaudally.","Koplik spots are pathognomonic for measles and appear on the buccal mucosa before the rash develops.","The \u00273 Cs\u0027 of measles are cough, coryza, and conjunctivitis, which precede the rash."],"references":["CDC. Clinical Overview of Measles [Internet]. Measles (Rubeola). 2024. Available at: https://www.cdc.gov/measles/hcp/clinical-overview/index.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36070"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13841"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20788"},{"type":"media","id":"20789"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20788","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20788"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cVZUJTtS3PWABkAs7tsETGVMYLOabb.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cVZUJTtS3PWABkAs7tsETGVMYLOabb.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":768,"height":1024}},{"type":"media","id":"20789","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20789"},"attributes"